Somewhat unnuanced;
"At stake, however, was not really the ruling party, its policies, or even the general direction of the nation."
Majority of Singaporeans are not interested in politics, period. Implicit in this statistical observation is that they are satisfied with the government, or else they would be interested in influencing change in government policies. HENCE, it makes much less sense for policies or the general direction of the nation to matter in the election. The pervasive feeling that analogous processes are implied to face the same circumstances as those in Western democracies (and that their presence should effect to similar results, even) really does not do justice in conveying the local nuance of government and politics in Singapore. 

The constraints of other modern nations make democracies and DEMOCRATIC PROCESSES intuitive - even rational - but these stabilising political processes should not be abstracted away from its context to embody it with some inherent, acontextual virtue. As was emphasised in the video, Singapore's development would have be impossible to instate in conjunction with conventional democratic systems. In that respect, within the BRIEF history of Singapore politics, much of the democratic freedoms currently espoused in Western countries are historically CONTRARY to the values which have led to prosperity within Singapore.

To ignore this context and reduce Singapore to just another authoritarian regime BUT WITH an anomalously successful economy does not make sense;
and while I admit that much of this video is merely informative, hence that my issue is with the minor effect, the implication that Singapore is just some miracle authoritarian regime on some invisible precipice of political collapse is just WRONG, or at least, unreasonable.

@17:09 well thats the trade off isnt it. PAP cant afford to screw up, if anything that keeps them on their toes. This is not the US where any idiot like Trump/AOC/Sanders can make a bid for power, PAP is structured similar to a communist party in certain regards, instead of ideology they elect based on competancy(although putting LHL in the running was a bit dirty, he has proven himself to be a worth of his fathers legacy). 
The problem is Singaporeans are getting complacent, with economic inequality being a chief problem, even if it cant be solved reducing its worst effects can go a long way. Having lived in democracy i'd rather forsake some of my rights to a competantly run autocracy even if it doesmt have the longevity.
Countries with much to lose are unlikely to elect idiots to power.

@16:24 NY never actually banned soda. There was a proposed law that never went into effect because it was rightfully struck down by the courts. The courts enforcing the law to prevent such overreach is a pretty big difference in the way the two countries handle such things.

(Also, it wasn't so much of a ban on soda, as a limitation on how large of a cup they could sell you, and only applied to restaurants, not grocery stores, you would have still been able to get the stuff and drink it freely in public) 

Weird comparison, I think it makes more sense to just skip trying to "but what about" the US and carry on with the real point that you bring up next instead. That these "quirks"  (or, draconian policies, depending on how you look at it) are only superficial differences between Singapore and the rest of the world, and are not why Singapore is fundamentally different.

Singapore is what Mainland China thinks it is, if it conveniently ignores how S'pore
1) celebrates multiculturalism;
2) admittedly relies on foreign immigrants;
3) maintains armed forces that don't project its presence against their neighbors;
4) doesn't tolerate even rumors of corruption by officials at any level; and
5) allows open challenges to the ruling party, even in the face of declining popularity
